{"instruction": "What is the vanishing gradient problem in neural networks and how can it be addressed?","context":"","response":"The vanishing gradient problem occurs when gradients become too small during backpropagation, leading to slow or ineffective training of deep neural networks. This can be addressed using techniques like using activation functions that mitigate vanishing gradients (e.g., ReLU), initializing network weights properly, and using gradient clipping."}
{"instruction": "Explain the concept of overfitting in deep learning and how it can be prevented.","context":"","response": "Overfitting occurs when a model performs well on the training data but poorly on unseen data. It can be prevented by using techniques such as regularization, dropout, and early stopping."}
