{"instruction": "Explain the concept of frozen layers in transfer learning and how they are used in fine-tuning.","context":"","response":"Frozen layers refer to layers in a pre-trained model that are kept fixed during fine-tuning to prevent them from being updated. This allows the model to retain the knowledge learned from the source task while adapting to the new task."}
{"instruction": "Discuss the concept of node purity in Random Forests.","context":"","response":"Node purity in Random Forests refers to how homogenous the target variable values are in a node. The goal is to split the data in a way that maximizes node purity, leading to more accurate predictions and better performance of the model."}
{"instruction": "How do reactive agents differ from deliberative agents in multi-agent systems?","context":"","response":"Reactive agents act based on stimulus-response mechanisms, while deliberative agents employ reasoning and planning to make decisions. Reactive agents are faster but less flexible, while deliberative agents are slower but more adaptive."}
